Generated when an SFF that supports Digital Diagnostic Monitoring (DDM) enters a failed state.
The tPortEgrVPortHostMatchFailure notification indicates that a host match lookup failed to resolve a specific port egress virtual port.
The notification tmnxResvCbsPoolThreshRed is generated when a reserved-CBS of an object (MDA or port) has crossed the threshold value specified by tmnxObjectAppRedAlrmThresh.
tmnxEqPortEtherCrcAlarm is generated when an Ethernet port CRC alarm condition is detected. It is generated only when the type of alarm being raised is enabled on the port.
tmnxEqPortEtherInternalAlarm is generated when an Ethernet port experiences excessive internal MAC tx errors. It is generated only when tmnxPortEtherDownOnInternalError is enabled on the port.
Received the same magic number from the peer as the local magic number. The channel may be looped back.
The system could not create a new PPPoE session in the tmnxPppoeSessionTable. The problem is described in the managed object tmnxPppoeSessionFailureReason.

The tmnxRadSrvPlcySrvOperStateCh notification is sent when the value of the object tmnxRadSrvPlcySrvOperState changes. A RADIUS server is reported as 'outOfService' when the system does not receive timely responses from that server, according to the values of the objects tmnxRadSrvPlcyTimeout and tmnxRadSrvPlcyRetry. It is reported as 'overloaded' when the system crosses the pending-requests-limit for that server.

The tmnxCpmProtExcdSapEcm notification is generated when an Eth-CFM packet stream (identified by a source MAC address, domain level, and Eth-CFM opcode) arrives at a local SAP at a rate which exceeds the configured Eth-CFM rate limit for the stream.
Generated when the license becomes invalid for the reason specified in tmnxSysLicenseErrorReason.
The tmnxSysLicenseExpiresSoon notification is generated when the license is due to expire soon.
The tmnxSysLicenseActivated notification is generated each time a license is activated on the system.
Generated when the standby detects a licensing failure. The reason is specified in tmnxSysLicenseErrorReason.

The tmnxSysLicenseUpdateRequired notification is generated once after the system boots up and the license is determined by the system to be valid, but requires to be updated to the correct software version.

The SNMP agent was started. The coldStart trap signifies that the SNMP entity, supporting a notification originator application, is reinitializing itself and that its configuration may have been altered.
The SNMP agent was re-started. A warmStart trap signifies that the SNMP entity, supporting a notification originator application, is reinitializing itself such that its configuration is unaltered.

A linkDown trap signifies that the SNMP entity, acting in an agent role, has detected that the ifOperStatus object for one of its communication links is about to enter the down state from some other state (but not from the notPresent state). This other state is indicated by the included value of ifOperStatus.
The tmnxSapStpExcepCondStateChng notification is generated when the value of the object sapTlsStpException has changed, i.e. when the exception condition changes on the indicated SAP.
There was a change in the administrative or operating status of a service.
The booked bandwidth that has been allocated to the SDP bindings exceeded the maximum bookable bandwidth.
A RADIUS accounting request was not sent out successfully to any of the RADIUS servers in the indicated accounting policy.
The operational status of a Radius server, configured for use with DHCP radius authentication, has transitioned either from inService' to 'outOfService' or from 'outOfService' to 'inService'.

The operational status of a Radius server, configured for use with DHCP radius based subscriber accounting, has transitioned either from 'inService' to 'outOfService' or from 'outOfService' to 'inService'.
ARP Host populate is enabled and upon the reception of an ARP message, an ARP host could not be instantiated. The failure reason is specified in the svcArpHostPopulateError.

The svcMacFdbTblFullAlarm notification is raised when system limit of FDB records is reached. Further traps are not generated as long as the value of svcMacFdbRecords object remains under 5 percent of the limit. The system limit of Backbone MAC address indices was reached.
Failed to update or create a SLAAC host in tmnxSubSlaacTable.
The tmnxSubHostLcktLimitReached notification indicates that the system wide maximum number of lockout hosts is reached.
The configuration phase following a system reboot has completed.
The SNMP daemon initialization completed following a system reboot. Some system configuration and initialization errors might have resulted in the SNMP daemon being suspended.

In a system with redundant CPM cards, upon completion of the bootup configuration synchronization was 'disabled' but the boot options file (bof) specifies the system is to be booted with persistent SNMP indexes.
Synchronization of redundancy information onto the standby CPM was started. tmnxChassisNotifyHwIndex identifies the standby CPM.
The system was unable to store persistency data (e.g. because the storage device is inaccessible, or full)."
The bootup failed script file is not accessible.
The tmnxSysRollbackSaveStatusChange notification is generated upon the completion of a rollback save as specified by tmnxSysRollbackFileType.
The persistencyFileSysThresRaised notification is generated when the filesystem reaches 90 percent occupation.

Change in status of "sysMGMCSwitchOverStatus" of the switchover which is over-enforced on the mobile gateway "sysMGMCSwitchOverMobGwId" belonging to the peer "sysMGMCSwitchOverPeerAddress" participating in the georedundancy.
The tmnxWppHostAuthenticationFailed notification is sent when a WPP host could not be authenticated. More detailed information is supplied in the object tmnxWppNotifyDescription.
A change occurs in the reference point peer state for the Diameter application.
The Charging Data Functions (CDF) peer is slow to respond or is not responding to RF ACR messages. From a Diameter connection perspective, the peer is still in service.
Compact flash capacity is low because a CDF outage has occurred and accounting messages are stored locally on the compact flash of the gateway.
A working card failure, change in the redundancy configuration, or a protect card addition triggers a change to the group redundancy state.

A card failure changes the card redundancy state to NOTVALID. When an active card goes down, the standby card becomes active which triggers a state change to active. When a STANDBYINPROG card becomes in sync with the active card, the state changes to standby.
The operating state for RADIUS server is changed to the down state.
All the RADIUS servers for the group are in a down operating state.
A change in the GTP Prime Server Group State.
A change in the action of writing CDR packets to the compact flash.
The maximum number of PDN connections for this APN on the gateway is reached.
The set of internal parameters for ICC call latency and memory utilization reach the high threshold (activated), and/or fall below the low threshold for at least some time period (de-activated).
The IPv4 or IPv6 address pool usage reaches the configured threshold because the IPv4 or IPv6 address pool is close to being exhausted.
The UE ID load count for the MSCP group crosses the 80% threshold.
The card goes down and is not able to be restored.

A change in the operational state of the overlay fabric switch, either when the last operational overlay fabric port transitions to the down state or when the first overlay fabric port transitions to an operationally up state.
The maximum number of PDN activations per second for this APN on the gateway is reached.
The ratio between tmnxMobGwIpsecLockoutUserLocked and tmnxMobGwIpsecLockoutUserAttched is over the tmnxMobGwIpsecLockoutUserThr threshold.
The subdirectories used to store Ga CDR files on the CF containing the maximum number of files per subdirectory reach the maximum number of subdirectories.
The compact flash (CF) card is full causing Ga CDR files to be written to another CF card.
A loss of connectivity to other cards in a particular direction over all available overlay fabrics.
Loss of connectivity between the affected card and the other cards in a particular direction over a particular overlay fabric.

The Association state changes when association is either setup or released. The association can be setup/released by association related Node level messages triggered by either the gateway or the peer. Association Messages are initiated by the gateway if the peer is configured in association Peer list.
The IPv4 or IPv6 address pool usage reaches the configured threshold because the IPv4 or IPv6 address pool are close to being exhausted.
The resources for the mobile gateway group have reached their limit.
The resources for the mobile gateway group have been almost exhausted due to high load.
Traffic is detected at the ICR node due to a network issue.
The resources for the mobile gateway group have reached their limit.
The resources for the mobile gateway group have been almost exhausted due to high load.
The GTP-based S11 attach rate exceeds the configurable limit.
Loss of connectivity to the NRF, NRF failure.
The IPv4 or IPv6 CAM usage reaches the configured threshold because the IPv4 or IPv6 CAM is close to being exhausted.
Either Create Session Requests are not received for the last 30 seconds, or the resources for the mobile gateway group are back to normal operating levels in the last 30 seconds.
The downlink buffer utilization exceeds the configured threshold.
All SWm peers are in down state.
PFCP Association Setup failure to establish due to Node ID missing.
The GTP-based attach rate exceeds the configurable max-session-attach limit for tmnxMobGwNtfyApnName is reached
PFCP-u tunnel used for via-up-function (radius-group or dhcp-server-group) traffic between CP and UP function is failing to get established/re-established.
The call failure monitoring task has detected call failures for more than the configured threshold rate and has persisted for the configured monitor timer value.

The call failure monitoring task has detected call failures for more than the configured threshold rate and has persisted for the configured monitor timer value. This has happend for two active cards consecutively within time limit.

The call failure monitoring task has detected call failures beyond the configured threshold rate and has persisted for the configured monitor timer value. The group is placed into the internal suspended state, as requested by the call failure rate monitoring task due to two consecutive active cards has higher failure rate within time limit.
PFCP Association Setup failure to establish due to mismatch of the provided node ID value from all of the PFCP association peer list configuration.
PFCP Association Setup failure to establish due to mismatch of the provided node ID IP-type value with all the configured SX reference point entry interface address types.
The SCP peer has been blocked.
The GTP echo request message queue has reached the configured limits of queue depth and sustained for the specified time interval.
The df2-peer's operational state will change when the TCP connection's state to the df2-peer changes.
The df3-peer's operational state will change when the TCP connection's state to the df3-peer changes.

The alarm is raised when a BGP peer has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up. 
The alarm is raised when the GMPLS peer's Administrative State is Up and the Operational State is Down. The alarm clears when the GMPLS peer's Operational State changes to Up or the Administrative State changes to Down. 
The alarm is raised when the Administrative State of a peer changes from Up to Down. The alarm clears when the Administrative State returns to Up.

The alarm is raised when a BGP peer has a Connection State other than Established, and the Administrative State of the BGP peer is Up.
The alarm is raised when the connectionState of this peer changes from Established to a state other than Established. The alarm clears when the connectionState of this peer returns to the Established state.

The alarm is raised when a BGP peer group has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when the Administrative State of a peer group changes from Up to Down. The alarm clears when the Administrative State returns to Up.
The alarm is raised when a BGP instance has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when a temperature crosses a threshold.
The alarm is raised when the compositeEquipmentState attribute has a value of equipmentMissing.
The alarm is raised when the compositeEquipmentState attribute has a value of equipmentMismatch.
The alarm is raised when the compositeEquipmentState attribute has a value of equipmentOperationallyDown.
The alarm is raised when a port has no associated physical link or remote end point is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when an IS-IS site has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when all ports in a LAG are operationally down.
The alarm is raised when an LDP site has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when an LDP targeted peer is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when the Operational State of an LSP is Down, but the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when an LSP path is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when an MPLS site has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.

The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects that a service tunnel is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when an MPLS path has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P cannot be added to the NE's SNMP trap destinations.
The alarm is raised when the SNMP Index Boot Status on an NE is not set to Persistent.

The alarm is raised when an interface or underlying resource fails, as indicated by an interface compositeState attribute value of failed or underlyingResourceFailed.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects that a redundant interface is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when an L2 management interface has an Operational State of Down, and the associated VPLS site has an Administrative State of Up.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects that an interface is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when a provisioned MTU size value is greater than the supported MTU size value.
The alarm is raised when a RIP group has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when a RIP site has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when an RSVP session is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when an RSVP site has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports an LOC condition, which causes the NE to set the port Operational State to Down.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports an LAIS error. The alarm corresponds to the lais alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a line remote defect indication error caused by an LOF, LOC, or LOS condition. The alarm corresponds to the lrdi alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a section synchronization failure. A section synchronization failure occurs when the S1 byte is inconsistent for eight consecutive frames.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a section error condition that a remote NE raises because of b1 errors received from the local NE. The alarm corresponds to the lrei alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a line signal degradation BER error. The alarm corresponds to the lb2er-sd alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a line signal degradation BER error. The alarm corresponds to the lb2er-sf alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a SLOF error. The alarm corresponds to the slof alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a SLOS error. The alarm corresponds to the slos alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports an SS1F error. The alarm corresponds to the ss1f alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a section synchronization failure. A section synchronization failure occurs when the S1 byte is inconsistent for eight consecutive frames.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a line error condition that a remote NE raises because of b1 errors received from the local NE. The alarm corresponds to the lrei alarm on an NE.

The alarm is raised when all SAPs on a site are operationally down, or when the service tunnels for the site are operationally down. For Backhaul Sites, this alarm is raised when one or more Backhaul Adjacencies is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when an ingress or an egress label is missing.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P fails to back up a set of NE configuration files.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P fails to restore a set of NE configuration files.
The alarm is raised when the admin save command on an NE fails.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS1 or E1 channel has an AIS alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS1 or E1 channel has an RAI alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS3 or E3 channel has an AIS alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS3 or E3 channel has an LOS alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS3 or E3 channel has an OOF alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS3 or E3 channel has an RAI alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS3 or E3 channel has a remote loopback alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS1 or E1 channel has an LOS alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS1 or E1 channel has an OOF alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS1 or E1 channel has a remote loopback alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when the license items in the network exceeds 100 percent of the license capacity.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a PAIS error. The alarm corresponds to the pais alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a PLOP error. The alarm corresponds to the plop alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a remote PAIS error. The alarm corresponds to the pais alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a path error condition because of b3 errors. The alarm corresponds to the prei alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a PPLM error on a channel, after which the channel is set operationally down. The alarm corresponds to the pplm alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a path error condition that a remote NE raises because of b3 errors received from the local NE. The alarm corresponds to the prei alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when no RD is configured for an L3 service site.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a path unequipped error. The alarm corresponds to the Path Alarm Unequipped Path Error alarm on an NE.

The alarm is raised when a I/O card or control processor or power-supply tray reports a failure. When the object type is ControlProcessor, a CPM may be unable to boot. When the object type is Power Supply Tray and the alarm is raised during device discovery, a power-supply tray may be out of service. When the object type is a Power Supply Tray and the device is in the managed state, a power-supply tray may be out of service or the AC power shelf has a fault condition. The alarm clears when the status changes to OK.
The alarm is raised when the bundle Administrative State is Up and the Operational State is Down.
The alarm is raised when an IGMP site has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.

The alarm is raised when the number of MAC address entries in the FIB reaches or exceeds the VPLS site high watermark specified by l2fwd.SiteFib.highWatermark. The alarm clears when the number of MAC address entries in the FIB drops below the VPLS site low watermark specified by l2fwd.SiteFib.lowWatermark. The alarm can be raised against a VPLS site, L2 access interface, or spoke SDP binding.

The alarm is raised when one or more files in the NFM-P software image specified for a device software upgrade is invalid, corrupt or absent. The NFM-P validates a device software file set before it imports the file set and distributes it to an NE. Ensure that the file set downloads properly to the NE and is not tampered with before you re-attempt the upgrade. The alarm clears when a valid file set is on the NE and the NFM-P activates the software image in the file set.
The alarm is raised when persistence is set to Off in the NE BOF.
The alarm is raised when a PIM site is administratively Up but operationally Down. The alarm is cleared when the PIM site becomes operationally Up but administratively Down.
The alarm is raised when the CCAG Administrative State is Up and the Operational State is Down.
The alarm is raised when an SDP binding has an Operational State other than Up.
The alarm is raised when an SDP binding tunnel has an Operational State other than Up.

The alarm is raised when a mediation poll of the SysUpTimeAlarm object on an NE fails, for example, because of network congestion or because the NE is too busy to respond. The probable cause is an unreachable NE Mediation agent on the NE. The polling interval depends on the NE type and is configurable in nms-server.xml. By default, the NFM-P polls a managed NE every four minutes. If a poll fails, the alarm is raised. The alarm clears when the NFM-P receives a response from the NE, and the NFM-P GUI icon that represents the NE turns from red to green.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P main or auxiliary server cannot transfer an accounting file from an NE.
The alarm is raised when a SONET port reports a PLCD error. The alarm corresponds to the plcd alarm on an NE.
The alarm is raised when an L2 or L3 interface operational state is Down. The alarm is not raised against an L2 access interface that is associated with an MC ring or MC LAG in the standby state.
The alarm is raised when the primary subscriber identification script is operationally down, but one of the other scripts is operationally up.
The alarm is raised when all subscriber identification scripts are operationally down.

The alarm is raised when the trapDroppedRaisesAlarm parameter is enabled and the maximum allowed number of SHCV host connectivity loss events on a SAP is exceeded. The SHCV action in response to the alarm is specified by the maxHostLostConnectivityRate parameter. If the specified action is to remove the host information, the host information is removed and the connectivity of the host is not subsequently verified.

The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects that an SRRP instance is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects that a VRRP instance is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when a peer configuration cannot be found on the peer NE.

The alarm is raised when the members of an MC LAG do not have matching configurations.
The alarm is raised when there is a peer configuration mismatch that prevents MC operation.
The alarm is raised when a SAP detects an STP exception condition, for example, one-way communication or a downstream loop. The alarm clears when the STP condition changes.
The alarm is raised when a device reports a signal failure on an Ethernet port.
The alarm is raised when a device reports a remote fault on an Ethernet port.
The alarm is raised when a device reports a local fault on an Ethernet port that is administratively up.
The alarm is raised when a device reports No Frame Lock on an Ethernet port.
The alarm is raised when a device reports a high bit-error rate on an Ethernet port.
The alarm is raised when a main server cannot communicate with an auxiliary server. The alarm clears when communication is restored.
The alarm is raised when an MSDP site is administratively down. The alarm clears when the site is administratively up.
The alarm is raised when the value of tmnxPppLocalMagicNumber is the same as the value of tmnxPppRemoteMagicNumber, which indicates that the link may be looped back.
The alarm is raised when a RADIUS accounting request is not successfully sent to any of the RADIUS servers specified in the RADIUS accounting policy.

The alarm is raised when the number of DHCP lease-state entries on a SAP reaches the configured maximum value. This value is defined by sapTlsDhcpLeasePopulate for a TLS VLAN service, and by vRtrIfDHCPLeasePopulate for an IES or VPRN service.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P is unable to proxy a DHCP request.
The alarm is raised when the chassis temperature exceeds the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when all ports in an MC LAG are operationally down.
The alarm is raised when a subscriber interface is operationally down. The alarm clears when the subscriber interface is operationally up.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects that a group interface is operationally down. The alarm clears when the group interface is operationally up.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects one or more malformed packets.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects a packet loss.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects a jitter buffer overrun.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects a jitter buffer underrun.
The alarm is raised when a device detects a physical loop on an Ethernet port.
The alarm is raised when the compositeEquipmentState attribute has a value of containingEquipmentMismatch.
The alarm is raised when the compositeEquipmentState attribute has a value of containingEquipmentOperationllyDown.
The alarm is raised when the temperature of an SFP or XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the temperature of an SFP or XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the supply voltage of an SFP or XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the supply voltage of an SFP or XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the transmit bias current of an SFP or XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the transmit bias current of an SFP or XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the output power of an SFP or XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the received optical power of an SFP or XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the manufacturer-specific Auxiliary 1 of the XFP reaches the minimum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the manufacturer-specific Auxiliary 1 of the XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the manufacturer-specific Auxiliary 2 of the XFP reaches the minimum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when the manufacturer-specific Auxiliary 2 of the XFP reaches the maximum threshold value.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS1 or E1 channel has an SD alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when an NE reports that a specific DS1 or E1 channel has an SF alarm condition.
The alarm is raised when a MEP loses connectivity with one or more remote MEPs. The Remote MEP DB State tab on a MEP lists the missing remote MEPs.
The alarm is raised when a MC ring group Operational State is not in the Connected state. The alarm is cleared when the ring group enters the Connected state.

The alarm is raised when the local RNCV Operational State of a ring node is other than Connected or NotTested, which means that the ring node is not connected to the local MC ring group. The alarm clears when the ring node enters the Connected or NotTested state.

The alarm is raised when the remote RNCV Operational State of a ring node is other than Connected or NotTested, which means that the ring node is not connected to the local MC ring group. The alarm clears when the ring node enters the Connected or NotTested state.
The alarm is raised when the restore procedure on an NE fails because of a mismatch between the backup file set version and the NE software version.
The alarm is raised when a chassis power supply is removed.
The alarm is raised when the deviceState attribute has a value of deviceNotEquipped.

The alarm is raised when the number of MRP attribute table entries for a service site exceeds the high watermark specified by l2fwd.SiteMrp.mrpAttrTblHighWatermark. The alarm clears when the number of MRP attribute table entries for the site drops below the low watermark specified by l2fwd.SiteMrp.mrpAttrTblLowWatermark.
The alarm is raised when an MLD site has an Operational State other than Up, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when the peer does not exist or the neighbor address does not point to a network interface on the NE that contains the peer object.
The alarm is raised when the associated fan is not operationally Up.

The alarm is raised when a power-supply tray reports a failure. When the alarm is raised during device discovery, a power-supply tray may be out of service. When the alarm is raised while the device is in the managed state, a power-supply tray may be out of service or the AC or DC power shelf has a fault condition. The alarm clears when the status changes to OK.
The alarm is raised when an ISA-AA group Operational State is Down, and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when an NE detects an STP exception condition on a SAP, for example, one-way communication or a downstream loop. The alarm clears when the STP status changes.
The alarm is raised when a sham link is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when a client delegate server is unreachable.
The alarm is raised when an EPC instance is operationally down but administratively up.
The alarm is raised when a card migration event fails.
The alarm is raised when the Operational State of an ISA video group is Down and the Administrative State is Up.

The alarm is raised when the S2L path Administrative State is Up and the Operational State is not Up. The alarm clears when the S2L path Operational State changes to Up or the Administrative State changes to Down.
The alarm is raised when an MC peer does not exist, or when an MC peer exists but the peer address is not the address of a network interface on the peer.
The alarm is raised when the peer port does not exist, or when the peer port exists but the synchronization tags of the peers do not match.
The alarm is raised when the VLAN ranges on the Multi-Chassis synchronization peers do not match.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P cannot find the peer MC ring.
The alarm is raised when a video interface is operationally down. The alarm clears when the video interface is operationally up.
The alarm is raised when a device reports an encoder degradation on a wavelength tracker interface.
The alarm is raised when a device reports an encoder failure on a wavelength tracker interface.
The alarm is raised when a device reports a power control degradation on a wavelength tracker interface.
The alarm is raised when a device reports a power control failure on a wavelength tracker interface.
The alarm is raised when a device reports a power control high limit on a wavelength tracker interface.
The alarm is raised when a device reports a power control low limit on a wavelength tracker interface.
The alarm is raised when the IGH is administratively up but none of the IGH protocols is operationally up.
The alarm is raised when the Operational State of a SAP IPsec gateway changes to Down and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when the IPsec tunnel operational state changes to 'down' and the administrative state is 'up'.
The alarm is raised when an MG group goes down.
The alarm is raised when an L2TP site becomes administratively down. The alarm clears when the L2TP site becomes administratively up.
The alarm is raised when a device reports a single-SFM overload. The alarm clears when the VR exits the Overload state.
The alarm is raised when a DSC service container is down.
The alarm is raised when a DSC service container is down.
The alarm is raised when an MPLS path update fails because of an MBB problem. The alarm clears when the MBB status changes to Successful.
The alarm is raised when a peer configuration cannot be found on the peer NE.
The alarm is raised when an MC endpoint is operationally down.

Deprecated in 10.0, Use {NatIsaMemberSessionUsageHi on nat.IsaMember} instead. The alarm is raised when the session usage of an ISA-NAT group member reaches the high watermark. The alarm clears when the session usage reaches the low watermark.

This user-defined alarm is raised when the NE is unable to send traps because the NE configuration is one of the following: - The Management IP Selection is set to Out Of Band Only, the Primary Route Preference is set to In Band, and the Secondary Route Preference is set to None. - The Management IP Selection is set to In Band Only, the Primary Route Preference is set to Out Of Band, and the Secondary Route Preference is set to None.
The alarm is raised when the Operational State of an ISA-LNS group is Down and the Administrative State is Up.
The alarm is raised when the associated power supply is not operationally Up.
The alarm is raised when the chassis temperature falls below the minimum threshold.
The alarm is raised when a low-temperature threshold is crossed.
The alarm is raised when the physical link is operationally down.
The alarm is raised when the node being discovered can not be properly identified.
The alarm is raised when an NE notifies the NFM-P that it cannot create a PPPoE Session.

The alarm is raised when a configuration fallback is detected on the node and comes back up with a previous configuration. To correct this situation it might be necessary to reconfigure the node, or perform full resync its database with the 'fallback' configuration returned by the node.

The alarm is raised when a configuration misalignment has been detected on the node and comes back up with an unexpected configuration (configuration change triggered by external tool) To correct this situation it might be necessary to reconfigure the node with the NFM-P's old configuration or accept the new configuration received from the node.
The alarm is raised when an LDP session is non-existent.

The alarm is raised when an NE notifies the NFM-P that it cannot create a PPPoA Session.

The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects that an AARP interface is operationally down.

The alarm is raised when the session usage of an ISA-NAT group member reaches the high watermark. The alarm clears when the session usage reaches the low watermark.
The alarm is an indication for abnormal condition on NE.

The alarm is raised when the P2MP LSP Administrative State is Up and the Operational State is Down. The alarm clears when the P2MP LSP Operational State changes to Up or the Administrative State changes to Down.

This alarm is generated when an output failure occurs on the power module.

GwLciOverload alarm is generated when either the LCI value is at or above 100%.

GwOciOverload alarm is generated when OCI overload levels have been reached.
The alarm is raised when connection to CBAM fails.

A PfcpLciOverload notification is generated when the PFCP LCI value is either at or above 100%. [CAUSE] The resources for the mobile gateway group have reached their limit. [EFFECT] The mobile gateway group resources are at critical levels. The system will attempt to lower resource usage on this mobile gateway group. [RECOVERY] None

A pfcpOciOverloadClear notification is generated when resources that had been over PFCP OCI limit have now fallen below OCI alarm levels. [CAUSE] The resources for the mobile gateway group are back to the  normal operating levels. [EFFECT] The mobile gateway group is back to the normal operating  levels. [RECOVERY] None, the system is back to the normal operating levels.

'A GwThrsMaxS11AtAct alarm is generated when the GTP-based attach rate exceeds the configurable limit. [CAUSE] The GTP-based attach rate exceeds the configurable limit. [EFFECT] If there is a new GTP-based attach and attach rate has been exceeded, the new attach will be rejected. [RECOVERY] The alarm is cleared when the rate goes back below the limit.'

This alarm is generated when either the IPv4 Content-Addressable Memory (CAM) usage reaches 90% of the CAM size. [CAUSE] The IPv4 CAM usage reaches the 90% threshold because the IPv4 CAM are close to being exhausted. [EFFECT] If the utilization of IPv4 CAM reaches 100%, the PGW rejects requests for new PDN connections. [RECOVERY] If the utilization of the IPv4 CAM reaches 100%, the operator's assistance is needed to remove rules from the configuration.

This alarm is generated when IPv6 Content-Addressable Memory (CAM) usage reaches 90% of the CAM size. [CAUSE] The IPv6 CAM usage reaches the 90% threshold because the IPv6 CAM are close to being exhausted. [EFFECT] If the utilization of IPv6 CAM reaches 100%, the PGW rejects requests for new PDN connections. [RECOVERY] If the utilization of the IPv6 CAM reaches 100%, the operator's assistance is needed to remove rules from the configuration.

This alarm  is generated when downlink buffer utilization exceeds the limit as configured. [CAUSE] The downlink buffer utilization exceeds the configured threshold. [EFFECT] The GW drops downlink packets when the buffer is full. [RECOVERY] None.

This alarm is generatedA  when the mobile gateway system group loses connectivity to all of its SWm peers. [CAUSE] All SWm peers are in down state. [EFFECT] MG group is not available for load balancing. [RECOVERY]  None.
The alarm is raised when the NFM-P detects one or more chassis in VC setup are shutdown.

A GwPfcpViaUpFuncFailure notification is generated when PFCP-u tunnel used for via-up-function (radius-group or dhcp-server-group) traffic between CP and UP function is failing to get established/re-established..
The alarm is  generated when the GTP-based attach rate exceeds the configured max-session-attach limit value.
